data.value:
Shows which encoder achieved the best compression efficiency for this specific test configuration.

Conditions:
• Only appears when 2 or more encoders are tested;
• Same input file and parameters for all encoders;
• Based on the smallest output file size;
• Calculated after 'Analyze Log' processing;

Not all encoder builds yield the same output size even with:
• Same source file;
• Identical parameters;
• Same encoder version.

This helps identify:
• Different compiler optimizations;
• Platform-specific code variations;
• Undocumented algorithm differences;
• Build configuration inconsistencies.

This allows direct compression ratio comparison between different encoders under identical conditions.

Average CPU load during encoding/decoding. For a single pass, this is the average load during that specific pass.
After 'Analyze Log', this shows the average CPU load across all passes for this test configuration.

For multi-threaded workloads, the value represents total CPU capacity used:
• 100% = 1 core fully utilized;
• 800% = 8 cores fully utilized;
• 3200% = 32 cores fully utilized;

This format better reflects multi-core scaling efficiency in parallel workloads.

Detects whether different encoders produce bit-identical file sizes under identical conditions.

Conditions:
• Only appears when 2 or more encoders are tested;
• Same input file and parameters for all encoders;
• Calculated after 'Analyze Log' processing;

Consistency of processing speed across all passes for this test configuration (ratio of median to 90th percentile of speeds).
Calculated after 'Analyze Log'.

Measures how consistent the processing speed is across all test passes.
Interpretation:
• 100% = Perfect consistency (no speed variation);
• 90% = High consistency (minimal variation);
• 70% = Moderate consistency;
• <50% = High variation in processing speeds;

Higher values indicate more stable and predictable performance across multiple runs.

